1390.Comment: I'll never forget that morning that he died. I live in L.A. County, walked outside to get the newspaper, and could barely see through the thickness of the fog. It was unbelievably foggy and remained that way for most of the morning. I received a text message from my sister, asking me if it was true that Kobe died in a helicopter crash. My heart felt like it stopped, yet, I thought it was absurd. I searched online and there were ZERO reports about his death. She bartends and one of the customers who had just walked in told her he found out that his friend had just died in a helicopter crash, along with Kobe. I turned on the TV and NOTHING was on. I flipped channels frantically. Then my mom said that someone on the radio confirmed it. I kept flipping the channels and finally, one channel broke in with the news. It was like I had to see it to believe it. He was my age. I wasn't his biggest fan, but my God, I cried every day for a week. ğŸ’”

2021.Comment:
As I rapidly near my 40s, I want to share an impact Conan O'Brien had on my life and my mental health. I was born from first-generation immigrant parents. My parents struggled to make ends meet, gain proper citizenship, follow the letter of the law to a tee, and of course fight to put me through the 'best' public schooling taxes could buy, in a privileged, somewhat gated community. Back when I was in high-school, my humanities teacher made some reference to Conan O'Brien during her lesson. Being a somewhat novice to late night American television culture (and let me remind you kids, this was in the days before smartphones and Google even existed), back then I innocently raised my hand and asked who Conan O'Brien was. My teacher gave me one cynical look, and immediately ordered the student sitting behind me to smack me on the back of the head with their notebook. Next thing I know, I felt the back of my head make swift, stinging contact with the student's aluminum spiral binded 100 page notebook, while I felt all the heavily disapproving stares and comments from all the rest of the 22 or so students in my class who likely assumed I was culturally inept to belong in their country, let alone community. In hindsight it sounds ridiculous now but, back then I really believed I had committed a grave sin worthy of discipline low-key reminiscent to a teacher in a dictatorship disciplining me for not immediately acknowledging or respecting a reference to the current leader.

All this to say, after watching this video, it finally dawned on me why my teacher acted in the manner she did that day. I had simply not recognized a such a great Late Night Talk Show legend in the making; Conan O'Brien, my sincerest apologies to you ğŸ™‡â€â™‚ï¸ğŸ™ may you live a long and healthy blessed life.â¤

This video brought back some good memories. This one time a buddy and neighbor of mine who is a retired NAVY SEAL needed some extra money. So he was given a US government assassination project in Bosnia. He was really excited about it. So one night he came over like a kid on Christmas to show me his new specs before being deployed. He had a new silencer and a red laser toy for his pistol. I let him in and he said, "Check this out!" He screwed the silencer into the barrel and turned out the lights. He put a bead around the room before putting it right between my eyes then over to my then future first ex wife. He and I started laughing and I told him, "Hell yeah man that's freaking cool!" She freaked out and started screaming. lol So we had to calm her down before he left. The next morning two FBI agents showed up at my door asking if I know this guy and about him buying a silencer and laser specs. I said, "Yeah. He's a friend and neighbor of mine who bought those specs legally in part of an assassination project in Bosnia he is about to leave for. He's a good guy go talk to him." Those agents just stared at me a moment. Then looked at each other then back at me. Then said, "Oh. Well, we just wanted to make sure you are comfortable with that information. Do you feel safe?" I said yes. So they went to talk to him. Later that day he came over to my place looking pissed and said, "Did you talk to the FBI about me?" I said, "Yeah of course I did man!" He asked what I told them and I replied. He stared at me for a tic then said, "Oh my God thank you bro!" Then gave me one those gross sweaty man hugs. Afterwards we threw a party for him at my bosses house who was in Air America for the CIA to send him off. Which ironically one my female coworkers who was drunk off her ass called me an asshole for no reason, other than my then girlfriend was a twat. Long story short, he completed his mission and came home safely. Haven't seen any of those people since. Aside from when I had to go to work for the DoD a short time after. Dude in the video looks just like him. Funny ole world isn't it? He is a big ole marshmallow truthfully. A titty baby. I tried to invite the FBI agents inside to chill but they weren't interested in all of that though. I got banned from Tik Tok and Facebook for talking about these things. 7684.Comment:
I feel like you couldve done better with that $40. That $8 monorail was unnecessary if youre going on a budget. Im from LA, so not a Nevada resident. There was a day where i was by myself and i did something similar to this because i didnt want to gamble. Spent time with one group of friends from Sunday to Wednesday, then they left on Thursday and i was by myself since my other group of friends were coming from Friday to Sunday. I booked my complimentary two nights for wed night and thursday night since most comp nights are available from sunday to thursday. So i spent entire Thursday by myself and ive tried something similar. I stayed at the Orleans but their shuttles are free to everyone and it connects u from Orleans all the way to the Strip near Harrahs and also to Downtown Vegas near Fremont. I took full advantage of this. So not a single penny on transportation. I did cheat because i put Grey Goose in my large flask. But there are places i drank such as Stage Door Casino where its only $1 beer, $2 patron shots. Ate at Blondie's for brunch for $7($5 + tax + tip), Ellis Island for dinner for $13($9.99 steak special + tax + tip). Walked around entire strip. There's also a small spot i forgot what it was called but ate a slice of pizza in the middle for $3.(pizza sucked. I dont recommend it. Wish i knew the name of the place so i can tell people not to go there.) I checked out nearly every casino and signed up for player's card and came with free play $10-$25 and thats the only way i gambled. Bought a Vegas shotglass for $5. While gambling using free play money, i got myself bunch of free drinks plus tip(each drink and i spent $10 on tips, so over 10 drinks).
$7 Blondies for brunch
$13 Ellis Island steak special
$5 stage door casino(1 shot patron, 1 beer + $2 tip)
$5 souvenir shotglass
$10 tips for drinks while playing games
$3 nasty pizza
Total: $43
Of course, i had a large 8oz flask of Grey Goose. So that helped a lot to make sure im wasted. ğŸ˜

Norma, may I give you a small tip? The proper way to eat a baguette, or any piece of bread, with your meal is to:
1. Place some of the butter on your little plate.
2. Place some of the bread on your little plate.
3. Tear off a bite size piece of your bread on your plate.
4. Butter just that little piece, using the butter on your little plate.
5. Put the entire bite-sized piece into your mouth.
Doing it this way saves you from gnawing awkwardly on a loaf of baguette. ğŸ˜‰

This is such a mind f**l in terms of London geography I had to click on KT just to understand how many things went wrong with this image.

So. If i were to look at the big ben and parliament from the opposite side of Westminster, to being with, the big ben and parliament would be on the left, not right.
Sono considered "maybe this image is flipped?" But it still did not make sense for how it would look from the south bank and that's when I realised the building next to the big ben are actually the other side of the bridge. Follow me: it means that flr how the buildings are placed the bridge should actually be going from right to left, not from top to bottom of this image. I lived in londong for a decade so my best guess is: the background of the picture with the big ben and buildings is actually shown from the perspective of the pedestrian bridge next to Charing cross railway bridge. And the "bridge" we see coming towards us that poses as Westminster bridge Is actually just a random bridge (also because Westminster bridge does not have a rail to divide the pavement from the road).
